Some useful predictos

These are some predictors that are frequently used in time series prediction data:

Trend

A linear trend can be modelled by uing \(X_{1,t}\) as a predictor:

\[\begin{align*} y_{t}= \beta_0+\beta_1t+\varepsilon_t \end{align*}\]

This can be easily within the TSLM() model using the trend() special.

Piecewise trend. Example

Let us look at the downwards trend of the Boston marathon times.

We extract mens data and convert winning times to a numerical value. we first fit a linear trend model:

boston_men <- boston_marathon %>%
  filter(Year >= 1924) %>%
  filter(Event == "Men's open division") %>%
  mutate(Minutes = as.numeric(Time)/60) %>%
  select(Year, Minutes)

boston_men
# A tsibble: 96 x 2 [1Y]

 3  1926    146.
 4  1927    160.

 7  1930    155.

 9  1932    154.
10  1933    151.

boston_men %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = Year, y = Minutes)) +
  labs(y = "Consumption (quarterly % change)",
       x = "Income (quarterly % change)") +
  geom_line() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", formula="y ~ x", se = FALSE)

TSLM_boston <- 
  boston_men %>%
  model(TSLM(Minutes ~ trend()))

resid <- TSLM_boston %>% augment() %>% select(Year, .innov)

resid %>% autoplot()
Plot variable not specified, automatically selected `.vars = .innov`

The residuals clearly show a growing pattern from 1975 onwards. This indicates that that the linear assumption does not hold, particularly from 1980 onwards. This is clearly visible in the timpeplot of the data, since the winning times seem to stagnate from 1980 onwards. Most of the reduction in winning times takes place between 1950 and 1980. We will fit a piecewise linear regression with two knows, one at 1950 and one at 1980.

  • NOTE: subjective identification of the notes can lead to overfitting and should be performed with caution.
fit_trends <- boston_men %>%
  model(
    linear = TSLM(Minutes ~ trend()),
    piecewise = TSLM(Minutes ~ trend(knots = c(1950, 1980))),
    exponential = TSLM(log(Minutes) ~ trend())
  )

fc_trends <- fit_trends %>% forecast(h = 10)

boston_men %>%
  autoplot(Minutes) +
  geom_line(data = fitted(fit_trends),
            aes(y = .fitted, colour = .model)) +
  autolayer(fc_trends, alpha = 0.5, level = 95) +
  labs(y = "Minutes",
       title = "Boston marathon winning times")

Dummy or indicator Variables

If the predictors are categorical variables we can use dummy variables to encode them.

Binary categorical variables

An example in the time series context would be public holiday âyesâ or ânoâ. Other examples could be the encoding of male vs.Â female or any variable that has two possible levels.

This type of binary variables can be encoded with just one dummy variable (a variable that can take two values: 0 and 1).

  • Value 0 would be assigned to one of the levels

  • Value 1 would be assigned to the other level.

Categorical Variable \(d1\) (associated dummy)
yes 1
no 0
no 0
no 0
yes 1
â¦ â¦

Dummy variable trap

If we decided to use two dummy variables instead of one to encode the categorical variable in the manner depicted by the table below:

Categorical Variable \(d1\) (associated dummy) \(d2\) (associated dummy)
yes 1 0
no 0 1
no 0 1
no 0 1
yes 1 0
â¦ â¦

We would incur in the so-called dummy variable trap. Variables \(d1\) and \(d2\) are not independent. At any given point in the dataset they satisfy an underlying equation: \(d1 + d2 = 1\). In other words, there is perfect multicollinearity between these two variables (the variables are not independent). This results in a matrix for the linear model that does not have full rank and, as a result, a model that is not properly defined.

Therefore, when encoding a categorical variable using dummies, one of the levels should be used as base and assigned a 0 value.

Categorical variables with more than one level:

The variable can be coded using several dummy variables. Specifically one fewer than the total number of categories to avoid the dummy variable trap:

  • TSLM() handles this automatically if a factor variable is specified as a predictor. There is usually no need to manually create the corresponding dummy variables.

The coefficients associated to each of thes dummy variables would be the measure of the effect of that category relative to the ommitted category. The following example should clarify further.

Seasonal dummy variables (ex: days of week)

A specific case is using the day of the week as a categorical predictor. The corresponding dummy variables would have the following form:

\(d_{1,t}\) \(d_{2,t}\) \(d_{3,t}\) \(d_{4,t}\) \(d_{5,t}\) \(d_{6,t}\)
Monday 1 0 0 0 0 0
Tuesday 0 1 0 0 0 0
Wednesday 0 0 1 0 0 0
Thursday 0 0 0 1 0 0
Friday 0 0 0 0 1 0
Saturday 0 0 0 0 0 1
Sunday 0 0 0 0 0 0
Monday 1 0 0 0 0 0
â¦ â¦ â¦ â¦ â¦ â¦ â¦

In the example below the coefficient associated to the variable \(d_{1,t}\) would measure of the effect of Monday relative to Sunday (the base level for which we have assigned only zeros).

Example: Australian quarterly beer production

recent_production <- aus_production %>%
  filter(year(Quarter) >= 1992)
recent_production %>%
  autoplot(Beer) +
  labs(y = "Megalitres",
       title = "Australian quarterly beer production")

We want to forecast the value of future beer production using a trend as well as a quarter factor variable. \(d_i,t = 1\) if \(t\) is in quarter \(i\) and 0 otherwise. Note that only 4-1 = 3 dummy variables have been included. The associated coefficients are measures of the difference between those quarters and the first quarter.

In the formulation below, trend() and season() are âspecialâ functions that work with the TSLM() formulation.

Fourier series terms

Jean-Baptiste Fourier showed that a series of sine and cosine terms of the right frequencies can approximate any periodic function. This, of course, is utmost useful for seasonal patterns in time series.

The mathematical underpinning of Fourier analysis exceeds the scope of this course, but is important that you are familiar with the fundamental ideas and understand how they apply in the context of time series. Here we are interested in noting that a series of sines and cosines can be used to obtain a base with sufficient rank to capture the seasonal pattern in our time series.

Let \(m\) be the seasonal period. The first few Fourier terms associated to this periodic signal would be:

\[\begin{align*} x_{1,t} = \sin\left(\textstyle\frac{2\pi t}{m}\right), x_{2,t} = \cos\left(\textstyle\frac{2\pi t}{m}\right), x_{3,t} = \sin\left(\textstyle\frac{4\pi t}{m}\right),\\ x_{4,t} = \cos\left(\textstyle\frac{4\pi t}{m}\right), x_{5,t} = \sin\left(\textstyle\frac{6\pi t}{m}\right), x_{6,t} = \cos\left(\textstyle\frac{6\pi t}{m}\right),\\ \end{align*}\]

and so on. Note that the higher the terms, the higher their frequency. The periodic signal would be the addition of all these terms:

\[\begin{align*} y_t = \sum_{k=1}^{K}[\alpha_k s_k(t)+\beta_k c_k(t)] + \varepsilon(t) \end{align*}\]

Instead of encoding the seasonal pattern using a dummy variable associated to each subdivision of the period as before, we could use the first m-1 terms of the Fourier series to obtain an alternative algebraic base to encode the dummy variables. \(m-1\) to avoind the dummy variable trap. For example for quarterly data (\(m=4\)), let us examine the first four Fourier terms:

The associated vector set for each of these functions within a season would be (see red points)

{

[0, 1, 0, -1], (associated to \(sin(0.5 \pi t)\))

[0, 0, 0, 0], (associated to \(sin(\pi t)\))

[1, 0, -1, 0], (associated to \(cos(0.5 \pi t)\))

[1, -1, 1, -1] (associated to \(cos(\pi t)\))

}

When using dummy variables, the associated vector set was:

{

[1, 0, 0 , 0] (first quarter)

[0, 1, 0, 0] (second quarter)

[0, 0, 1, 0] (third quarter)

}

If we pick three linearly independent vectors from the fourier base, we may use these to model the seasonal pattern and arrive to an equivalent linear model. The coefficients associated to each vector will be different, but the vectors will combine to represent the seasonal pattern in the same manner. Let us check this:

fourier_beer <- recent_production %>%
  model(TSLM(Beer ~ trend() + fourier(K = 2)))
  report(fourier_beer)

The K argument to fourier() specifies how many pairs of sine and cosine terms to include. Due to the colinearity considerations made before for categorical variables, the maximum allowed is \(K = m/2\), where \(m\) is the length of the seasonal period. Here we have used the maximum (\(4/2 = 2\)) and so we arrive at an equivalent model with the exact same Adjusted R-Squared, residual standard error and degrees of freedom. Note as well that only three fourier terms (\(m-1\)) have been included. The formulation in the fable() library already picks \(m-1\) linearly independent terms.

If we set up K = 1, the seasonal pattern would be modeled using a single pair of sin and cosine functions. The associated base would look like this:

{

[0, 1, 0, -1], (associated to \(sin(0.5 \pi t)\))

[1, 0, -1, 0] (associated to \(cos(0.5 \pi t)\))

}

Fourier vs dummy variables

With Fourier terms, we often need fewer predictors than with the dummy variable approach to model a seasonal pattern with a similar level of accuracy, especially if m is large. This makes them useful, for example, for weekly data, where \(m = \approx 52\). Other examples could be hourly data, where \(m = 24\).

For short seasonal periods (e.g.Â ) quarterly data, there is little advantage in using Fourier terms over seasonal dummy variables.

Second Fourier Example

aus_cafe <- aus_retail %>% filter(
    Industry == "Cafes, restaurants and takeaway food services",
    year(Month) %in% 2004:2018
    ) %>% summarise(Turnover = sum(Turnover))

aus_cafe %>% autoplot(Turnover)

We would now like to fit models a growing number of pairs of sin-cosin Fourier terms:

fit <- aus_cafe %>%
  model(
    K1 = TSLM(log(Turnover) ~ trend() + fourier(K = 1)),
    K2 = TSLM(log(Turnover) ~ trend() + fourier(K = 2)),
    K3 = TSLM(log(Turnover) ~ trend() + fourier(K = 3)),
    K4 = TSLM(log(Turnover) ~ trend() + fourier(K = 4)),
    K5 = TSLM(log(Turnover) ~ trend() + fourier(K = 5)),
    K6 = TSLM(log(Turnover) ~ trend() + fourier(K = 6)),
  )

Intervention variables

Some events may have affected the variable to be forecast:

  • Competitor activity

  • Unusual advertising expenditure

  • Industrial actionâ¦

If the effects last only for one period, we use a âspikeâ variable. This variable takes value one in the period and zero elsewhere. It is equivalent to a dummy variable for handling an outlier.

If the effects of the intervention are permanent, we use a âstepâ dummy. Takes value zero before the intervention and one from the time of the intervention onwards.

A change of slope can also be considered an intervention. This is handled using piecewise linear regression.

NOTE REGARDING NONLINEAR TRENDS: using non-linear trends for forecasting is not recommended, since they tend to result in exxagerated forecasts when extrapolating into the future. It is usually better to use piecewise linear trends if possible.

Example intervention variable

The data set souvenirs concerns the monthly sales figures of a shop which opened in January 1987 and sells gifts, souvenirs, and novelties. The shop is situated on the wharf at a beach resort town in Queensland, Australia. The sales volume varies with the seasonal population of tourists. There is a large influx of visitors to the town at Christmas and for the local surfing festival, held every March since 1988. Over time, the shop has expanded its premises, range of products, and staff.

souvenirs %>% autoplot(Sales)

The timeplot of the data shows that:

  • The data is seasonal (similar pattern created every year)

  • A spike every March (except 1987) due to the surfing festival

  • Size of the seasonal pattern increases proportionally to the level.

Let us take logarithms to turn the additive scheme into a multiplicative scheme:

# Taking logarithms of the data<
souvenirs %>% autoplot(log(Sales))

  1. Create a dummy variable that takes value 1 (TRUE) for every march exept for the year 1987 and 0 (FALSE) for the rest
souvenirs_dummy <- souvenirs %>%
  mutate(dummy_fest = (month(Month) == 3) & (year(Month) != 1987))

souvenirs_dummy

  1. Fit a regression model to the logarithms of the sales with:
  • a linear trend
  • seasonal dummies
  • a âsurfing festivalâ dummy variable

Plot the fitted valeues

fit <- souvenirs_dummy %>%
  model(reg = TSLM(log(Sales) ~ trend() + season() + dummy_fest))
souvenirs %>%
  autoplot(Sales, col = "gray") +
  geom_line(data = augment(fit), aes(y = .fitted), col = "blue")

We can see that a linear model combining all these regressors (linear trend + dummies for seasonality + dummy for festival event) is able to adequately capture many relevant features of the data

fit %>% gg_tsresiduals()

Looking at the residuals, we see that they are autocorrelated. Specifically their slow decay reveals some non-linearity in the trend that has not been accurately captured by the model and has bled down to the residuals.

augment(fit) %>%
  features(.innov, ljung_box, dof = 14, lag = 24)
# A tibble: 1 x 3
  .model lb_stat lb_pvalue
  <chr>    <dbl>     <dbl>
1 reg       112.         0

The timeplot of the residual appears to reveal some heteroskedasticity, which can be more clearly visualized using box-plots that group the values by month (not necessary, introduced as additional technique):

augment(fit) %>%
  mutate(month = month(Month, label = TRUE)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = month, y = .innov)) +
  geom_boxplot()

This reveals some potential heteroskedasticity of the residuals over time that may render the prediction intervals inaccurate.

The model could be improved by taking into account the non-linearity in the trend. Remember nonetheless that this is risky, because extrapolating non-linear trends can quickly lead to inaccurate forecasts. A piece-wise linear trend could be a better alternative to improve the fit of the model.

Including auto-regressive terms could help eliminate the autocorrelation of the residuals. This would nonetheless lead to a combination of an (see chapter on ARIMA models).

Regardless of these considerations, let us perform some forecasts to visualize the predictions given by such model. To do this, we need to specify new values for the variables that we defined manually. In this case the variable created manually is the dummy associated to the festival. Without these values the model is not able to generate forecasts:

future_souvenirs <- new_data(souvenirs_dummy, n = 36) %>%
  mutate(dummy_fest = month(Month) == 3)

fit %>%
  forecast(new_data = future_souvenirs) %>%
  autoplot(souvenirs_dummy)

Trading days

Sales data can be affected by the number of tranining days in a month. The number of trading days in each month can be used as a predictor to account for this.

Alternatively 7 variables can be created, each including the number of different days of the week as a predictor.

Lagged values of the predictor variables

The effect of a predictor can have an impact lasting beyond the point in time where it occurs. For example, advertising expenditure can have an effect beyond their actual campaign on the sales.

To account for that, lagged valued of those predictors can be included. For example:

\[\begin{align*} x_{1} &= \text{advertising for previous month;} \\ x_{2} &= \text{advertising for two months previously;} \\ & \vdots \\ x_{m} &= \text{advertising for $m$ months previously.} \end{align*}\]

It is usual that the coefficients are required to reduce as the lag increases.

Easter

Easter is preculiar because the exact date when it occurs changes from year to year. Also, its effect can last for several days.

A dummy variable can be used with value one where the holiday falls in the particular time period and zero otherwise.

With monthly data, if Easter starts in March and ends in April the dummy variable is split proportionally between both months.

Selecting Precitors

Usually there are many possible predictors. Basing the selection of variables on statistical significance is difficult:

  1. Statistical significance does not always indicate predictive value (see section 7.8).
  2. P-values can be misleading when two or more predictors are corelated

Instead we will use measures of predictive accuracy. We will use five such measures, following ref [1]

Adjusted \(R^2\)

See the foregoing section. As stated there, maximising \(\bar{R^2}\) works well for selecting predictos, but tends to lead to too many predictors.

Cross-validation

We can use a leave-one-out approach to select predictors. This procedure makes efficient use of the data and involves these steps:

  1. Remove observation \(t\) from the data set, and and fit the model using the remaining data. Then compute the error (\(e_{t}^*=y_{t}-\hat{y}_{t}\)) for the ommited observation. Note that this is an error and not a residual because this observation was not used in training the model.

  2. Repeat step 1 for \(t=1,\dots,T\)

  3. Compute the MSE from \(e_{1}^*,\dots,e_{T}^*\). We will refer to this as CV.

Under this criterion, the best model is the one with the smallest value of CV. The above steps are efficiently implemented within the galnce() function.

The figure below (ref [1]) is a depiction of the datasets necessary for the leave-one-out approach:

Akaikeâs Information Creterion

We now introduce a series of inormation criteria. The main idea behind these is to penalize the fitting of the model (minimization of SSE) with the modelâs complexity, accounted for via the number of parameters to be estimated.

Akaikeâs Information Crietrion is defined as:

\[\begin{align*} \text{AIC} = T\log\left(\frac{\text{SSE}}{T}\right) + 2(k+2), \end{align*}\]

where:

  • k is the number of predictors included
  • T is the number of observations.

^The model with minimum value of the AIC is often the best model for forecasting. For large values of \(T\), minimizing the AIC is equivalent to minimizing the CV value.

The AIC is developed using principles of Maximum Likelihood and negative entropy (Kullback-Liebleck divergence). The exact derivation of the AIC is somewhat beyond the scope of this course. The student is referred to ref. 3 to delve into the exact mathematical formulation of the model.

Corrected Akaikeâs Information Criterion

If \(T\) is small, the AIC tends to select too many predictors. The bias-corrected version of the AIC was developed for these smaller samples:

\[\begin{align*} \text{AIC}_{\text{c}} = \text{AIC} + \frac{2(k+2)(k+3)}{T-k-3}. \end{align*}\]

As with the \(AIC\), the \(AICc\) shall be minimized.

Schwarzâs Batesian Information Criterion

Alternatively named as \(BIC\), \(SBIC\) or \(SC\)

\[\begin{align*} \text{BIC} = T\log\left(\frac{\text{SSE}}{T}\right) + (k+2)\log(T) \end{align*}\]
  • The goal again is to minimise BIC.
  • BIC penalises the complexity (number of parameters) more than AIC.
  • BIC is based on selecting the model with the bigg

Recommended measures

We recommend that either \(AICc\), \(AIC\) or \(CV\) statistics be used for model selection, since they have forecasting as their objective. If T is large enough, they will all lead to the same model.

The table has been arranged by AIC:

  • In this case, the best model contains all four predictors
  • The first four models clearly outperform the rest. This indicates that savings and income are much more relevant than the rest of the variables.
  • The first three rows have almost identical values, so we could possibly drop Production or Unemployment and get similar forecasts. This is because Production and Unemployment are highly negattively correlated, so most of the predictive information is contained already in one of these variables.

Best Subset Regression

If possible, all potential models should be fitted and the best model should be selected. This is known as âbest subsetsâ or âall possible subsetsâ regression.

Stepwise regression

The number of potential models grows as the power of two ofthe number of predictors. Consequently, at some point it might be unfeasible to fit all the models. In this case **stepwise regression* makes more sense.

Stepwise regression is not guaranteed to lead to the best possible model, but it usually leads to a model that is good enough for forecasting.

Bakcwards stepwise regression

  1. Start with a model fitting all predictors
  2. Remove one predictor at a time. Keep the model if it improves the measure of predictive accuracy.
  3. Iterate until no further improvement

Forward stepwise regression

  1. Start with a model fitting only an intercept
  2. Add one predictor at a time and keep the one that improves the measure of predictive accuracy most.
  3. Repeat until no further improvement can be achieved.
